01:09.000 --> 01:11.924
<i>A day and a half</i>
after Deep water Horizon exploded,

01:12.000 --> 01:14.606
<i>the flames, fed by crude</i>
from the bottom of the sea,

01:14.680 --> 01:16.728
<i>were simply too big to contain.</i>

01:16.800 --> 01:19.201
<i>For the families</i>
of the 11 missing crew members,

01:19.280 --> 01:21.328
<i>hope of their rescue is fading.</i>

01:21.400 --> 01:24.529
<i>The search for survivors</i>
will end before dawn tomorrow.

01:24.600 --> 01:26.728
<i>The forced</i>
feeding of mud and cement

01:26.800 --> 01:28.848
<i>into the well failed to work.</i>

01:28.920 --> 01:32.970
<i>The well continues to spew oil</i>
with the force of seven fire hoses.

01:33.040 --> 01:36.647
<i>Today, that slick is 12 miles long,</i>
covering 100 square miles.

01:36.720 --> 01:39.405
<i>Winds are coming</i>
from the south and they're strong,

01:39.480 --> 01:42.802
<i>about 30 miles an hour,</i>
pushing that oil towards the coast.

01:48.000 --> 01:50.128
Congressman, all of our sites
are outlined here.

01:50.200 --> 01:53.283
We've got our east operations
all the way up here.

01:53.360 --> 01:54.930
Over here, our west operations.

01:55.000 --> 01:58.288
Up here we're working with local Indian
tribes to protect their burial grounds.

01:58.360 --> 02:00.249
How you doing on boom supply?

02:00.320 --> 02:02.800
Hard boom we clean and reuse,
so we're good there.

02:02.880 --> 02:05.247
Soft boom needs to be replaced
when it's oil soaked, so...

02:05.320 --> 02:07.163
demand is never ending.

02:16.440 --> 02:18.681
It's something new.

02:18.760 --> 02:21.604
It's something we had to figure out
on our own because we're shrimpers.

02:21.680 --> 02:24.160
We didn't know nothing about
cleaning up oil until last week.

02:24.240 --> 02:26.447
Floyd told me
you got six boats.

02:26.520 --> 02:28.841
BP contract them all?
Two of them.

02:28.960 --> 02:31.327
The other four shut down
because we ain't allowed to shrimp.

02:31.400 --> 02:33.164
How much are they paying you?

02:33.240 --> 02:35.402
1350 a day a boat.

02:35.480 --> 02:39.326
And out of that I got to pay for
fuel, crew, all the other expenses.

02:39.400 --> 02:42.688
Normally you'd be making what?
35? Yeah.

02:42.760 --> 02:44.967
Going to have to start
laying off workers soon.

02:46.200 --> 02:49.409
First Katrina took it away
and now BP.

02:50.800 --> 02:52.802
What you going to do?

03:13.760 --> 03:18.129
<i>The chair recognizes the</i>
gentleman from Louisiana, Mr. Pryce.

03:18.200 --> 03:20.009
<i>Thank you, Mr. Chairman.</i>

03:20.080 --> 03:23.004
<i>Today we saw reports</i>
that BP's spill in the Gulf

03:23.080 --> 03:25.686
<i>has grown to nearly</i>
20 million gallons,

03:25.760 --> 03:28.969
<i>which is roughly twice</i>
the size of Exxon Valdez.

03:29.040 --> 03:33.841
<i>This is the most devastating man-made</i>
environmental disaster in U.S. History.

03:33.920 --> 03:37.003
<i>It's also an economic</i>
and cultural disaster.

03:37.080 --> 03:40.687
People of the Gulf Coast
will be living with this reality

03:40.760 --> 03:44.003
long after the TV cameras
have gone home

03:44.080 --> 03:46.845
and the nation's attention
has turned elsewhere.

03:46.920 --> 03:50.288
Long after the politicians
have finished making their statements,

03:50.320 --> 03:53.005
these people
will continue to suffer.

03:56.040 --> 03:58.566
Today I'm not
a federal official.

03:58.640 --> 04:02.611
Today I'm a resident
of the Louisiana Gulf Coast.

04:02.720 --> 04:05.883
These fishermen,
these restaurant owners,

04:05.960 --> 04:08.645
these folks who run the bait shops
and the corner stores,

04:08.720 --> 04:11.724
they're people I grew up with.
They're people my parents grew up with.

04:11.800 --> 04:14.963
People I look in the eye
every single day.

04:15.040 --> 04:17.805
They've never asked
for a handout in their lives.

04:17.839 --> 04:21.322
They've bled for this country, their sons
and daughters have bled for this country,

04:21.399 --> 04:23.562
and right now
they need our help.

04:23.640 --> 04:28.771
They need firm commitments
from BP and the government

04:28.840 --> 04:31.081
that'll not just
help them rebuild,

04:31.160 --> 04:34.209
but that'll assure them
we stand by their side.

04:34.280 --> 04:36.760
That we have their backs
just like they've had ours.

04:40.920 --> 04:44.811
Everything I know,
everything I love is at risk.

04:46.840 --> 04:50.242
And even though these marshes
lie along coastal Louisiana...

04:51.880 --> 04:55.168
these are America's wetlands.

04:55.240 --> 04:58.801
And even though this is
British Petroleum's spill...

05:03.720 --> 05:07.361
it is America's ocean.

05:07.440 --> 05:10.603
Excuse me, I'd just like to submit the
rest of my statement for the record.

05:10.680 --> 05:12.761
Thank you.

06:18.240 --> 06:20.079
Been calling the house.

06:20.080 --> 06:21.889
I needed time to clear my head.

06:21.960 --> 06:23.530
That was quite
a show you put on.

06:23.600 --> 06:25.125
It wasn't a show.
I dropped the lines

06:25.200 --> 06:26.884
about the necessity
for a central czar.

06:26.960 --> 06:29.201
Most important part of the speech.
You were honest.

06:29.280 --> 06:31.521
And that's the way it came off.
No, I was weak.

06:32.080 --> 06:34.320
You haven't heard.

06:43.280 --> 06:45.521
Who else picked it up?
Everyone.

06:45.600 --> 06:47.443
Today it appears
the sun is shining

06:47.520 --> 06:50.000
on a Louisiana congressman
nobody knows.

06:50.520 --> 06:52.079
You want to milk this.

06:52.080 --> 06:54.447
I want to milk
the shit out of it

06:54.520 --> 06:56.160
and ride it straight
into the Senate seat.

06:56.200 --> 06:58.646
This is what
we've been waiting for.

07:01.120 --> 07:03.088
You're not capitalizing
on the spill.

07:03.160 --> 07:04.810
This...

07:04.840 --> 07:07.001
This is you.

07:07.160 --> 07:10.607
All right.
All right.

07:10.680 --> 07:12.967
We're going to use this, Frank,

07:13.040 --> 07:15.407
to ensure BP and Transocean

07:15.480 --> 07:17.482
take responsibility
for what they've done.

07:17.560 --> 07:19.847
Shine a light
in their goddamn faces.

07:21.440 --> 07:23.329
You're on the 9:15
out of Reagan.

07:26.400 --> 07:28.289
And Colin...

07:28.360 --> 07:31.489
if we're going to do this,
we need to be buttoned up.

08:27.360 --> 08:30.523
I want the Coast Guard
and the EPA closed to press.

08:30.600 --> 08:34.571
But Frank explicitly said... I don't
care what Frank said. This is priority.

08:34.640 --> 08:38.042
Let's keep this tasteful. Would
you consider 20/20 tasteful?

08:39.080 --> 08:42.289
They're going to open
with you on June 15th.

08:42.360 --> 08:44.488
It seems like this speech
is going to have some legs.

09:03.840 --> 09:08.323
Congressman, care to
comment on yesterday's speech?

09:08.440 --> 09:12.047
Jen, how you doing this morning?
Hanging in there, sir.

09:12.120 --> 09:15.124
Unfortunately, the congressman requested
this be a closed-door meeting.

09:15.240 --> 09:18.528
Sorry, folks.
Are you running for Senate?

09:18.600 --> 09:21.524
Since you were last here, we've made
a significant number of changes.

09:21.600 --> 09:24.285
Just trying to be more
aggressive containing the oil.

09:24.360 --> 09:26.522
How often are you receiving
shipments of soft boom?

09:26.600 --> 09:28.399
Not often enough.

09:28.400 --> 09:30.448
<i>I'll</i> see what I can find
out and circle back.

09:30.520 --> 09:33.649
If you need anything else, you call me.
You've got my personal number.

09:33.720 --> 09:37.122
Yes, sir.
Thank you.

09:39.040 --> 09:41.407
Enlighten me, Mr. Morris,
who do I need to call

09:41.480 --> 09:43.847
to get trucks bringing in
soft boom every day?

09:43.920 --> 09:46.651
Admiral Allen?
Goddamned president?

09:46.720 --> 09:50.406
No, no, no. Believe me, I understand,
and I'm not trying to be rude.

09:50.480 --> 09:51.879
I'm just sick
of all this posturing.

09:51.880 --> 09:53.689
You don't think I've been
through this before?

09:53.760 --> 09:56.445
Katrina, Rita, Gustav, Ike.

09:57.760 --> 10:00.047
Thank you. That's all
I wanted to hear.

10:02.880 --> 10:05.451
Louisiana needs
the oil industry

10:05.520 --> 10:07.887
and the oil industry
needs Louisiana.

10:08.000 --> 10:11.561
That was true 100 years ago
and it will be true in another 100 years.

10:11.640 --> 10:15.486
The spill was a tragedy,

10:15.560 --> 10:20.327
but it is in everyone's best interest
to keep American oil healthy.

10:21.000 --> 10:23.446
My husband isn't
doubting how reliant

10:23.520 --> 10:25.761
our local economy
is on industry.

10:26.200 --> 10:28.931
My fund runs a diversified
energy portfolio

10:29.000 --> 10:31.002
with an emphasis
on Gulf producers.

10:31.080 --> 10:34.243
I know you've leaned left
on energy in the past,

10:34.360 --> 10:38.126
but I'm looking to back a horse
that will support our interests.

10:38.240 --> 10:40.129
You can find a lot
of politicians around here

10:40.240 --> 10:42.163
in the party whose interests
align with yours.

10:42.240 --> 10:44.766
Why me?
You're a winner.

10:47.400 --> 10:50.563
People are talking about you, Congressman.
Even in my world.

10:50.640 --> 10:53.723
Well, then, you should know
I don't pander to campaign financing.

10:53.800 --> 10:57.691
Well, you won't win the Senate seat
unless you reconsider.

10:59.360 --> 11:02.250
I'm sorry, I was under the
impression this was a lobby meeting.

11:02.320 --> 11:04.402
We haven't decided
if we're going to run for Senate.

11:04.480 --> 11:06.050
Colin, just hear him out.

11:06.120 --> 11:08.646
We are in the middle
of a recession.

11:08.720 --> 11:10.848
This election is going
to be about the economy.

11:10.920 --> 11:13.924
And a moratorium will be
more devastating than the spill itself.

11:14.000 --> 11:15.525
Mark, I don't think
you quite understand,

11:15.600 --> 11:17.762
I'm not just advocating
for a temporary moratorium.

11:17.840 --> 11:19.649
I think we ought
to phase out drilling altogether.

11:19.720 --> 11:22.485
<i>Colin.</i>
Oil is an addiction.

11:22.560 --> 11:26.804
And right now it's going to be pretty
damn tricky to deny how harmful it is,

11:26.880 --> 11:29.531
how antiquated it is.

11:29.600 --> 11:32.922
We need to develop
a sustainable infrastructure.

11:33.000 --> 11:34.923
Mark, you're a man
with foresight.

11:35.000 --> 11:38.607
You know green is how
we ought to be creating jobs.

11:38.680 --> 11:41.206
Am I hearing
what I think I'm hearing?

11:41.560 --> 11:43.085
I'm sorry.

11:43.120 --> 11:44.849
We've wasted your time.

11:45.880 --> 11:47.719
You're not going to win.

11:47.720 --> 11:50.131
We'll see.

11:50.600 --> 11:51.679
It's not smart.

11:51.680 --> 11:55.287
You told him we're planning to run
before we've announced.

11:55.400 --> 11:57.528
You humiliated me.

11:57.600 --> 12:01.650
Do you have any idea how much
business my firm does with that man?

12:01.720 --> 12:03.609
I didn't ask you to do that.

12:03.640 --> 12:06.166
I won't be beholden
to Mark Lavin or anyone else.

12:06.240 --> 12:08.925
<i>That speech was a godsend.</i>

12:09.000 --> 12:12.209
Don't blow it.

12:12.280 --> 12:13.799
What's wrong?

12:13.800 --> 12:15.319
Nothing.

12:15.320 --> 12:17.765
See you at home.

12:30.640 --> 12:34.042
Frank told me you've been
calling the office.

12:34.120 --> 12:36.600
Why would you do that?

12:36.680 --> 12:38.887
What were you thinking, Lucy?

12:38.960 --> 12:41.611
I'm sorry.

12:41.680 --> 12:43.523
Terrence knows about us.

12:45.320 --> 12:50.201
He came home drunk last night talking
all sorts of shit, and I don't know.

12:50.280 --> 12:52.248
But don't worry,
he ain't going to say nothing.

12:54.680 --> 12:56.330
I think you've had enough.

12:56.400 --> 12:57.970
Don't you think you've
fucking had enough?

12:58.040 --> 12:59.610
No.
I do.

13:06.880 --> 13:09.724
Okay, I'm sorry, Lucy, okay?

13:09.800 --> 13:12.290
I'm sorry.

13:13.280 --> 13:15.169
I miss you, Colin.

13:41.640 --> 13:43.449
Please.

13:44.160 --> 13:47.721
Just sit with me.
Just for a minute. Please.

14:27.240 --> 14:30.403
Tell it like it is, Pryce!

14:30.480 --> 14:32.960
You've got my vote.
All right, brother.

